<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>TSI 91-04-01 - Tractor Protection Valve Systems Operation</stitle>
    <tsi id="tsi910401" tsitype="truck">
        <tsinumber>91-04-01</tsinumber>
        <tsidate>March, 1991</tsidate>
        <subjectfile>BRAKES</subjectfile>
        <subjectgroup>
            <subject>Tractor Protection Valve Systems Operation</subject>
        </subjectgroup>
        <description>
            <geninfo>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>For the purpose of this bulletin, a truck is considered to be a tractor if it is equipped
                            to tow another air braked vehicle or trailer.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
                <para>Navistar-built tractors with air brakes (code 04092) are required by Federal law to have an air
                    brake system that protects the tractor air pressure against the effects of a loss of air pressure to
                    the trailer. The Office of Motor Carrier Safety states that the tractor air system shall be
                    protected in the range of 20 psi to 45 psi. Straight trucks with air brakes (code 04091) are not
                    affected by these regulations.
                </para>
                <para>Two different tractor protection systems are used on International tractors with air brakes.
                </para>
                <para>One system (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9104011">Figure 1</hotlnk>) uses a portion of the dash-mounted modular valve (MV-2
                    or MV-3) to control a tractor protection valve. The dash mounted modular valve senses low trailer
                    air pressure and sends a signal to trip the tractor protection valve. The trailer supply knob (red
                    octagonal) "pops" out, the tractor protection valve "trips" and the air supply to the trailer is cut
                    off.
                </para>
                <figure id="f9104011" figsize="pg-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G9104011.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 1. 4 X 2 Tractor With MV-2 Or MV-3 Dash Mounted Modular Valve Brake System</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. AIR COMPRESSOR</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. AIR COMPRESSOR GOVERNOR</callout1>
                        <callout1>3. LOW PRESSURE SWITCH</callout1>
                        <callout1>4. AIR GAUGE</callout1>
                        <callout1>5. SUPPLY RESERVOIR</callout1>
                        <callout1>6. DRAIN COCK</callout1>
                        <callout1>7. CHECK VALVE</callout1>
                        <callout1>8. SECONDARY RESERVOIR</callout1>
                        <callout1>9. PRIMARY RESERVOIR</callout1>
                        <callout1>10. PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE</callout1>
                        <callout1>11. QUICK RELEASE VALVE</callout1>
                        <callout1>12. HAND CONTROL VALVE</callout1>
                        <callout1>13. MODULAR TRACTOR PROTECTION VALVE CONTROL</callout1>
                        <callout1>14. TRACTOR PROTECTION VALVE</callout1>
                        <callout1>15. BRAKE VALVE</callout1>
                        <callout1>16. STOPLIGHT SWITCH</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
                <para>The other system (Three Line System) (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9104012">Figure 2</hotlnk>) uses separate dash-mounted valves. The trailer air
                    supply valve (red octagonal) is a push/pull valve that supplies air to the tractor protection valve.
                    The tractor protection valve senses system air pressure and trips automatically at 35 to 45 psi
                    cutting off the air supply to the trailer. The trailer supply valve on the dash
                    <emph type="bold">does not pop out</emph>
                    with this system.
                </para>
                <figure id="f9104012" figsize="pg-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G9104012.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 2. 4 X 2 Tractor Three Line Brake System (Two Separate Dash-Mounted Valves)
                    </caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. AIR COMPRESSOR</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. AIR COMPRESSOR GOVERNOR</callout1>
                        <callout1>3. LOW PRESSURE SWITCH</callout1>
                        <callout1>4. AIR GAUGE</callout1>
                        <callout1>5. SUPPLY RESERVOIR</callout1>
                        <callout1>6. DRAIN COCK</callout1>
                        <callout1>7. CHECK VALVE</callout1>
                        <callout1>8. SECONDARY RESERVOIR</callout1>
                        <callout1>9. PRIMARY RESERVOIR</callout1>
                        <callout1>10. TWO-WAY CHECK VALVE</callout1>
                        <callout1>11. PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE</callout1>
                        <callout1>12. QUICK RELEASE VALVE</callout1>
                        <callout1>13. HAND CONTROL VALVE</callout1>
                        <callout1>14. TRACTOR PROTECTION CONTROL VALVE</callout1>
                        <callout1>15. TRACTOR PROTECTION VALVE</callout1>
                        <callout1>16. BRAKE VALVE</callout1>
                        <callout1>17. STOPLIGHT SWITCH</callout1>
                        <callout1>18. SPRING BRAKE CONTROL VALVE</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
                <para>Both systems meet federal regulations for air brakes as stated by the Office of Motor Carrier
                    Safety and the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration.
                </para>
            </geninfo>
        </description>
        <svcproc svcproctype="test" graphiccount="0">
            <title>TEST PROCEDURE</title>
            <para>The following steps should be followed to verify proper actuation of the tractor protection valve.
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>The tractor protection valve cannot be tested by operating the service brake pedal.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Block wheels to prevent the vehicle from moving.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Build air pressure to governor cut off.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Shut down the engine.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Push in both dash valves.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Break the trailer
                    <emph type="bold">EMERGENCY</emph>air connection at the back of the cab enough to create a
                    <emph type="bold">slow</emph>
                    leak. Bleed the air down until no more air is exhausted. When the air stops bleeding off, the
                    tractor protection valve has tripped and is
                    <emph type="bold">PROTECTING</emph>the tractor air system. Neither dash mounted valve on a three
                    line system should move. On a system equipped with a dash mounted modular valve (MV-2 or MV-3), the
                    trailer supply knob (red octagonal) will have popped out.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Note the pressure remaining in the system on the dash gauge. If the system is operating
                    properly, the pressure reading will be in the range of 35 to 45 psi
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">The spring brake control knob will still be pushed in.</para>
            </step1>
            <para>The philosophy behind the Navistar system is that in the event of a pressure loss, the trailer air
                supply will be terminated first, protecting the tractor air supply. If the air loss continues, the
                tractor spring brakes will activate at a lower pressure.
            </para>
            <para>The pressures for automatic trip are listed below. (
                <hotlnk xrefid="t9104011">Table 1</hotlnk>).
            </para>
